    • rotate

      public static <T> void rotate(List<T> a, List<T> b, int distance)
      Rotate, in-place, across two lists. Elements at the end of the first list get moved to the beginning of the second list. Elements at the end of the second list get pushed to the first list.

      Similar in behavior to Collections.rotate(List, int) wherein negative distances rotate left and positive distances rotate right.

      Type Parameters:
      T - type of element in lists
      Parameters:
      a - first list
      b - second list
      distance - distance to rotate

    • a025480

      public static int a025480(int n)
      Corresponds to an integer sequence of the https://oeis.org/A025480 which generates the index positions for the proper sequence of swaps (and swap backs) for the interleave operation, given that series of swaps was done sequentially and in order. Implementation note: The algorithm effectively right shifts the value of n just past the lowest clear bit.
      Parameters:
      n - index on the left side to swap
      Returns:
      index on the right side to swap (plus any midpoint offset)

    • fastmod

      public static int fastmod(int n, long u64_c, int pd)
      Lemire's Fast Remainder by Direct Computation

      Requires pre-computation of a constant before calling

      For n % d where n and d are signed integers, u64_c is the multiplicative inverse of d given by: 

      
     int pd = d < 0 ? -d : d ; // divisor d can't be Integer.MIN_VALUE
     long u64c = Long.divideUnsigned( -1L, pd) + 1L +
          // skip when divisors are always positive
         ((pd & (pd-1L))==0 ? 1L : 0);

      Requires jdk 18

      Parameters:
      n - the dividend
      u64_c - unsigned multiplicative inverse of the divisor (see above)
      pd - unsigned absolute value of divisor, positive d.
      Returns:
      remainder of n % d
